          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
          Ethics in foreign aid 
       </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
        <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
         <strong>Summary: Is Switzerland making a difference with its development aid to improve democracy in Tajikistan?</strong>
         </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Switzerland has been <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-may-25-analysis-h1-9-helping-tajikistan" target="_blank">helping Tajikistan</a> for 25 years in human rights, governance, and digitalization. The country has worked to improve access to clean water, judicial aid, and education. Since 2022, Switzerland has committed $24M to various initiatives. They fund digitalization projects like civil registries and public service platforms to help the country improve overall transparency. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          However, analysts say that there has been little progress. Tajikistan <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-may-25-analysis-h1-10-remains-an-authoritarian" target="_blank">remains an authoritarian</a> state. President Emomali Rahmon has been in power for around 30 years, and civil liberties continue to decline. NGOs are frequently dissolved. There is little opposition, as most forms of it get silenced instantly. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Critics warn that digitalization can empower citizens but also give authoritarian governments more control. The UN repeatedly condemns Tajikistan‚Äôs human rights record and calls for direct support for rights defenders and NGOs. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Switzerland‚Äôs approach to promoting reform while working with an authoritarian regime raises ethical questions. Experts suggest that the Swiss government reduce its cooperation with the government and instead focus on grassroots efforts to support civil society in Tajikistan and countries like it. By 2028, Switzerland is set to spend $11.05M on digitalizing public services.</p>
        </mj-text>
